pr_body:
This PR is ready for review.
The associated tutorial to this PR can be found [here](https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/wiki/Electrical-Plug-Mating-Plugin).
This associated GitHub issue can be found [here](https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/issues/20). 

PR Summary:  
These are tutorial pictures used for the wiki
```
 tutorial_pictures/collision_socket.png          
 tutorial_pictures/electrical_mating_launch.png  
 tutorial_pictures/plug_on_platform.png
 tutorial_pictures/socket_on_bop.png
```          
These are files related to the plug and socket models
```
 uuv_dave/models/plug/model.config       
 uuv_dave/models/plug/model.sdf            
 uuv_dave/models/socket_box/model.config      
 uuv_dave/models/socket_box/model.sdf 
 uuv_mating/models/Electrical-Plug.dae           
 uuv_mating/models/Electrical-Socket.dae  
 uuv_mating/models/Inner-Plug.png      
 uuv_mating/models/Outer-Plug.png         
```
Files associated with the plugin
```
 uuv_mating/include/uuv_mating/uuv_mating.hh
 uuv_mating/src/uuv_mating.cc    
 uuv_dave/launch/uuv_dave_electrical_mate.launch       
 uuv_dave/worlds/uuv_dave_electrical_mating.world 
 uuv_mating/CMakeLists.txt               
 uuv_mating/package.xml               
```

pr_body:
In this PR I add the meshes obtained from Ryan to the robot arm. There are also few minor changes.

To test this PR, please run the following command.
```
roslaunch uuv_dave uuv_predator.launch
```


![predator_arm](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13877149/91655629-f0356a00-ea7f-11ea-8cea-3feccb30f19f.png)

__Picture of Predator arm attached to UUV__

**Summary of changes:**
- Add the meshes of the Predator arm links. 
- Removed an extra joint from the control files (it was left over from the oberson7).
- Change some PID values and friction and damping to remove oscillations from gripper.

**Issues with the current arm:**  
1. No texture: The individual links were not centralized. After I centralized them in Blender, the tag in the dae file responsible for texture disappears.
2. Collision = visual. No individual collision models with reduced textures was produced. âˆ´ , which may result in more collision computations than needed.  
3. There is a slight tilt in the arm at the initial position of the azimuth angle. The initial azimuth angle is set to be 0, however that slight tilt means it is not exactly at 0.

pr_body:
**Overview**
Added FT sensors to all arm joints and the gripper joints. (From Azimuth joint up to wrist, no FT sensors in the finger joints)  
Related wiki can be found [here](https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/wiki/Manipulator-Force-Feedback).
Video demonstrating functionality can be found [here](https://vimeo.com/422486993).
**Details**  

- Created a world with a springy place in it called `uuv_dave_ocean_waves_spring.world`
- new launch file `uuv_manipulator_spring_demo.launch` to launch the uuv in that world
- copied some urdf files from the manipulator repo to add the FT sensor functionality. These files are:

1. oberon7_default.xacro (paths were changed to open the serial arm from the uuv dave)
2. serial_arm.gazebo.xacro (ft sensors were added here)
3. serial_arm.xacro (ft sensor macro was added to this file)

- The `rexrov_oberon7.xacro` file was edited to open the new urdf files in the uuv_dave repo and not the manipulator arm.

[{'comment_id': 428664582, 'comment_body': '@bsb808 I just want to make sure I am understanding this right. This sensor tag is completely independent of ROS. All it does is publish wrench messages to a gazebo topic. So what I need to do to get this to a ROS topic is to write a ROS-aware plugin that reads those force_toruqe messages from the gazebo topic and republish them to a ROS topic.  
Is my understanding correct?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 13, 52, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Youssef-Khaky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428726723, 'comment_body': '@Youssef-Khaky Yes, you have explained it well.  This is a typical design pattern for Gazebo/ROS.  Working with both can feel a bit like loving in parallel universes simultaneously.  

I imagine you saw this tutorial - http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=force_torque_sensor&cat=sensors   The `gz topic` command is a good introspection tool to see the traffic, but not as well documented as `rostopic`

It looks like the `force_torque` gazebo sensor publishes a WrenchStamped gazebo message (protobuf) which you can see here - https://github.com/osrf/gazebo/tree/gazebo11/gazebo/msgs
I also typically take a quick look at the sensor code to better understand how it works - https://github.com/osrf/gazebo/tree/gazebo11/gazebo/sensors

There are at least two ROS plugins that do some of what you want.
 
1. The FT ROS plugin: https://github.com/ros-simulation/gazebo_ros_pkgs/blob/kinetic-devel/gazebo_plugins/src/gazebo_ros_ft_sensor.cpp .   This includes some noise.   Here is an example of using the sensor that looks reasonable: https://github.com/CentroEPiaggio/force-torque-sensor/blob/master/model/ft_sensor.gazebo.xacro  
2. F3D ground truth plugin: http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=ros_gzplugins  and https://github.com/ros-simulation/gazebo_ros_pkgs/blob/kinetic-devel/gazebo_plugins/src/gazebo_ros_f3d.cpp  which doesn't include noise.

You might take a look at the code for 1 and 2 to verify that they are doing the same thing with the exception of adding noise.

One thing I find useful in planning this type of thing is to draw a quick "boxes and arrows" sketch of what is going on.  Here is an example from the sonar effort:  https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/blob/master/docs/sonar_dev_arch.png
I use yEd to create the sketches.  It is nice b/c it is text based and fits well into repos.  In addition to getting things straight in my mind it helps to coordinate work with other and to make it more maintainable if folks have an idea of the high-level structure.  

I think you could start with the existing gazebo/gazebo_ros functionality to add a sensor to each joint, but it would be nice to automate the system such that a user could specify force feedback for an entire manipulator model and then the system would create the appropriate gazebo/gazebo_ros plugins for all the joints.  Might be able to do this with xacro or embedded ruby?

You might take a look at the HAPTIX project and ROS Industrial to make sure this doesn't exist somewhere.  Carlos wasn't aware of anything, but I'm surprised that it it isn't around and want to avoid reinventing any wheels.  If indeed isn't done it will be a really nice contribution.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 15, 26, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'bsb808', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428843882, 'comment_body': "These are good resources. Thank you.  
I will look into automating the entire manipulator arm's sensor attachment.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 18, 45, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Youssef-Khaky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 429255061, 'comment_body': "I am more in favour of the first one because it is applied to joints were the second one is applied to links. From my understanding, these kind of sensors are placed at the joints.  
Additionally, applying them at the joints means they have torque, the second one doesn't have torque since it is on links.  
I looked at couple of these sensors. The common configeration I have been noticing is putting those FT sensors at the base of an end-effector and not on every joint. Like [this](https://youtu.be/K5Z_pmBNrP8?t=65) video from Robotiq and [this](https://youtu.be/b4nz_hAh7qs?t=126) video from ATI.  Should we consider having it only at on the wrist joint?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 22, 13, 45, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Youssef-Khaky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 429491817, 'comment_body': 'I agree.  Using the FT sensors seems like the way to go.

I like the Robotiq demo video - I think doing something similar in gazebo would be really useful.  Having a spring to push against is a good idea!

We want to have feedback from all the joints.  The existing hardware gives feedback to teleoperators for each joint and we anticipate that will be a useful part of u/w manipulation where visibility is very limited.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 22, 23, 52, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'bsb808', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 430755694, 'comment_body': 'Nit - Can you clean up the line breaks and indentation.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 26, 23, 8, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'bsb808', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 430756335, 'comment_body': 'Start launch files with `<?xml version="1.0"?>` tag.

pr_body:
**Pull request overview.**
Added a new launch file that spawns the uuv in front of a bop panel. The purpose of this is to demonstrate the capability of the simulation and users can also use this to get used to controlling the manipulator.  

**Details**  

- `valve_manipulation_demo.launch`  

The launch file does the same thing as the `uuv_dave.launch` and also includes a launch file called `rexrov_oberon_arms_demo.launch` that spawns the uuv model with the position hold functionality.

- `uuv_dave_ocean_waves.world`  

Some light elements were added to the world to the panel can be visible.  
 

**Associated wiki:**  
https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/wiki/BOP-Panel-Manipulation-Mission.  
Comments
I am not sure if there is something wrong with the manipulator, but it is quite difficult to get it to hold tightly on the knob dial.  
It ends up looking something like this.
![manipulator](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13877149/81924457-2a502e00-95ad-11ea-9e71-6011f2817d44.png)

This associated GitHub issue can be found [here](https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/issues/20).

pr_body:
In this PR I add the meshes obtained from Ryan to the robot arm. There are also few minor changes.

To test this PR, please run the following command.
```
roslaunch uuv_dave uuv_predator.launch
```


![predator_arm](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13877149/91655629-f0356a00-ea7f-11ea-8cea-3feccb30f19f.png)

__Picture of Predator arm attached to UUV__

**Summary of changes:**
- Add the meshes of the Predator arm links. 
- Removed an extra joint from the control files (it was left over from the oberson7).
- Change some PID values and friction and damping to remove oscillations from gripper.

**Issues with the current arm:**  
1. No texture: The individual links were not centralized. After I centralized them in Blender, the tag in the dae file responsible for texture disappears.
2. Collision = visual. No individual collision models with reduced textures was produced. âˆ´ , which may result in more collision computations than needed.  
3. There is a slight tilt in the arm at the initial position of the azimuth angle. The initial azimuth angle is set to be 0, however that slight tilt means it is not exactly at 0.

pr_body:
**Overview**
Added FT sensors to all arm joints and the gripper joints. (From Azimuth joint up to wrist, no FT sensors in the finger joints)  
Related wiki can be found [here](https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/wiki/Manipulator-Force-Feedback).
Video demonstrating functionality can be found [here](https://vimeo.com/422486993).
**Details**  

- Created a world with a springy place in it called `uuv_dave_ocean_waves_spring.world`
- new launch file `uuv_manipulator_spring_demo.launch` to launch the uuv in that world
- copied some urdf files from the manipulator repo to add the FT sensor functionality. These files are:

1. oberon7_default.xacro (paths were changed to open the serial arm from the uuv dave)
2. serial_arm.gazebo.xacro (ft sensors were added here)
3. serial_arm.xacro (ft sensor macro was added to this file)

- The `rexrov_oberon7.xacro` file was edited to open the new urdf files in the uuv_dave repo and not the manipulator arm.

[{'comment_id': 428664582, 'comment_body': '@bsb808 I just want to make sure I am understanding this right. This sensor tag is completely independent of ROS. All it does is publish wrench messages to a gazebo topic. So what I need to do to get this to a ROS topic is to write a ROS-aware plugin that reads those force_toruqe messages from the gazebo topic and republish them to a ROS topic.  
Is my understanding correct?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 13, 52, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Youssef-Khaky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428726723, 'comment_body': '@Youssef-Khaky Yes, you have explained it well.  This is a typical design pattern for Gazebo/ROS.  Working with both can feel a bit like loving in parallel universes simultaneously.  

I imagine you saw this tutorial - http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=force_torque_sensor&cat=sensors   The `gz topic` command is a good introspection tool to see the traffic, but not as well documented as `rostopic`

It looks like the `force_torque` gazebo sensor publishes a WrenchStamped gazebo message (protobuf) which you can see here - https://github.com/osrf/gazebo/tree/gazebo11/gazebo/msgs
I also typically take a quick look at the sensor code to better understand how it works - https://github.com/osrf/gazebo/tree/gazebo11/gazebo/sensors

There are at least two ROS plugins that do some of what you want.
 
1. The FT ROS plugin: https://github.com/ros-simulation/gazebo_ros_pkgs/blob/kinetic-devel/gazebo_plugins/src/gazebo_ros_ft_sensor.cpp .   This includes some noise.   Here is an example of using the sensor that looks reasonable: https://github.com/CentroEPiaggio/force-torque-sensor/blob/master/model/ft_sensor.gazebo.xacro  
2. F3D ground truth plugin: http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=ros_gzplugins  and https://github.com/ros-simulation/gazebo_ros_pkgs/blob/kinetic-devel/gazebo_plugins/src/gazebo_ros_f3d.cpp  which doesn't include noise.

You might take a look at the code for 1 and 2 to verify that they are doing the same thing with the exception of adding noise.

One thing I find useful in planning this type of thing is to draw a quick "boxes and arrows" sketch of what is going on.  Here is an example from the sonar effort:  https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/blob/master/docs/sonar_dev_arch.png
I use yEd to create the sketches.  It is nice b/c it is text based and fits well into repos.  In addition to getting things straight in my mind it helps to coordinate work with other and to make it more maintainable if folks have an idea of the high-level structure.  

I think you could start with the existing gazebo/gazebo_ros functionality to add a sensor to each joint, but it would be nice to automate the system such that a user could specify force feedback for an entire manipulator model and then the system would create the appropriate gazebo/gazebo_ros plugins for all the joints.  Might be able to do this with xacro or embedded ruby?

You might take a look at the HAPTIX project and ROS Industrial to make sure this doesn't exist somewhere.  Carlos wasn't aware of anything, but I'm surprised that it it isn't around and want to avoid reinventing any wheels.  If indeed isn't done it will be a really nice contribution.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 15, 26, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'bsb808', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428843882, 'comment_body': "These are good resources. Thank you.

pr_body:
**Pull request overview.**
Added a new launch file that spawns the uuv in front of a bop panel. The purpose of this is to demonstrate the capability of the simulation and users can also use this to get used to controlling the manipulator.  

**Details**  

- `valve_manipulation_demo.launch`  

The launch file does the same thing as the `uuv_dave.launch` and also includes a launch file called `rexrov_oberon_arms_demo.launch` that spawns the uuv model with the position hold functionality.

- `uuv_dave_ocean_waves.world`  

Some light elements were added to the world to the panel can be visible.  
 

**Associated wiki:**  
https://github.com/Field-Robotics-Lab/dave/wiki/BOP-Panel-Manipulation-Mission.  
Comments
I am not sure if there is something wrong with the manipulator, but it is quite difficult to get it to hold tightly on the knob dial.  
It ends up looking something like this.
![manipulator](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13877149/81924457-2a502e00-95ad-11ea-9e71-6011f2817d44.png)
